@pram1 no problem! I see this fund trading in a range ~3.50-4.50 over the next few weeks... news events that prop up prices, but don’t have a fundamental catalyst, will be be faded quickly; and sell-offs that over extend fundamental market conditions will be bought up quickly... larger (retail) traders will be doing two things: 1) de-risking net short positions by slowly covering, but keeping recent short entries intact and 2) hedging recent short entries with strategic longer term calls, and possibly picking up small long positions at the low points.  However, as demand recovers and contango balances, the range will break to the upside and the edge will be with buying at support above the breakout of the range.  Institutional traders are likely avoiding $USO for now due to current demand risks and prices below $10 are not favorable to trade.

@hashtagg Eventually retail bulls are going to get tired of the stagnation, if only for a few weeks, and if they begin to pull out, the price will drop further not to mention roll yield with $USO.  With roll yield risk, you’re simply not going to see large traders get in “yet”.  I personally have locked in my profits on the short side of oil, as the risk to reward has now shifted, but it’s not quite time to go long - for oil, the fundamentals must support the price action, otherwise it’s likely a head fake.  I’m just saying, stay vigilant and be patient for a potential long entry... unless you have substantial amounts of capital, you have to maintain exposure to the market, and you’re required to have a position in a futures based oil ETF, and you can handle a potential %30 decline from current prices... I would wait for an entry.

@hashtagg I track and record the Time & Sales, open interest, and on-balance volume of the instruments I’m interested in trading or investing in... I agree that there have been many purchases of $USO  - I see the offers hit on the tape... the issue is that these are retail-sized orders (though there are many of them and they could very well be iceberg orders and other algorithmically obscured orders; this has only really kept the price above $4) — the issue is that the smart-money large traders (1MM+ shares) have been selling, which is why you don’t see the price go up... not even to $5 with all the retail bullishness.

@vrm @entry_level @TheBigCountry $ES_F $SPX $SPY yeah, price action and psychological S/R levels create “regions of interest” on the charts, but confirmation of direction by reaction to those regions is largely determined by order flow (the “tape” where market orders are filled).  To find out what the big traders are doing (or majority of traders), combine order flow with on-balance-volume (OBV) and changes in open interest (futures)... if short/mid-term OBV is flat or rising and price is dropping (but not dropping as fast), bulls are accumulating, and vice versa.
